      <lg type="edition">
<l>aṟavai neñcat tāyar vaḷaru</l>
<l>maṟavai neñcat tāyi vāḷa</l>
<l>rarumpalar cerunti neṭuṅkāṉ malarkamaḻ</l>
<l><gap quantity="26" reason="lost" unit="character"/>maṉṉa muṟṟat</l>
<l>tārvalar kuṟuki ṉallatu kāvalar</l>
<l>kaṉaviṉuṅ kuṟukāk kaṭiyuṭai viyaṉakar</l>
<l>malaikkaṇat taṉṉa māṭañ cilampaveṉ</l>
<l>ṉarikkuraṟ ṟaṭāri yiriya voṟṟip</l>
<l>pāṭi niṉṟa paṉṉā ḷaṉṟiyuñ</l>
<l>ceṉṟa ñāṉṟaic ceṉṟupaṭa riraviṉ</l>
<l>vantataṟ koṇṭu neṭuṅkaṭai niṉṟa</l>
<l>puṉṟalaip poruna ṉaḷiyaṉ ṟāṉeṉat</l>
<l>taṉṉuḻaik kuṟukal vēṇṭi yeṉṉarai</l>
<l>mutunīrp pāci yaṉṉa vuṭaikaḷaintu</l>
<l>tirumala raṉṉa putumaṭik koḷīi</l>
<l>makiḻtaraṉ marapiṉ maṭṭē yaṉṟiyu</l>
<l>mamiḻtaṉa marapi ṉūṉṟuvai yaṭicil</l>
<l>veḷḷi veṇkalat tūṭṭa laṉṟi</l>
<l>muṉṉūrp potiyiṟ cērnta meṉṉaṭai</l>
<l>yirumpē rokkal perumpulam pakaṟṟa</l>
<l>vakaṭunaṉai vēṅkai vīkaṇ ṭaṉṉa</l>
<l>pakaṭutaru cenneṟ pōroṭu nalkik</l>
<l>koṇṭi peṟukeṉ ṟōṉē yuṇṟuṟai</l>
<l>malaiyala raṇiyun talainīr nāṭaṉ</l>
<l>kaṇṭāṟ koṇṭumaṉai ṟiruntaṭi vāḻtti</l>
<l><gap quantity="39" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>vāṉaṟi yalaveṉ pāṭupaci pōkka</l>
<l>laṇṇal yāṉai vēnta</l>
<l>ruṇmaiyō vaṟiyal kāṇpaṟi yalarē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>You are virtuous at heart ??? (1)</l>
<l>You are valorous at heart ??? (2)</l>
<l>In the front yard that is like … (4)</l>
<l>fragrant of the long-stalked blossoms of the pear-tree with budding blooms, (3)</l>
<l>in the protected wide mansion that is not approached even in dream (6)</l>
<l>by watchmen, unless solicitors approach, (5)</l>
<l>besides the many days that I stood [there] singing, (9)</l>
<l>furtively(?) pressing my Taṭāri drum with grating voice (8)</l>
<l>so that storied buildings, that are like a group of mountain, rang, (7)</l>
<l>he, taking in [my] arrival (11ab)</l>
<l>at night that went [and] was leaving when I went (10)</l>
<l>saying: “pitiable is he, the ruddy-headed artist (12)</l>
<l>	who stands at the tall gate (11cd)</l>
<l>wanted [me] to come close to him, removed</l>
<l>the dress that was like lichen in old water from my middle (13f.)</l>
<l>put on [me] a new cloth that was like luminous blossoms, (15)</l>
<l>and besides the fermented liquor of the custom of giving delight/intoxication (16)</l>
<l>besides feeding [me] from a silver-white vessel (18)</l>
<l>with boiled rice [and] meat curry of a custom that is like ambrosia, (17)</l>
<l>[and], to dispel the great loneliness of my very big kinfolk (20)</l>
<l>with soft gait who had joined the public hall of the front town (19)</l>
<l>he granted, together with war, red paddy brought by bulls (22)</l>
<l>that looked like the blossoms of the kino tree wet in [its] belly, (21)</l>
<l>[and] said “let you get some of the plunder”. (23a-c)</l>
<l>If you see the man from the watery land whose head is adorned </l>
<l>with mountain flowers from the drinking ghat, (23d-25a)</l>
<l>although taking [him] in, praising his perfect feet (25b-d)</l>
<l>…………………………………… (26)</l>
<l>the heavens won’t know of the making go of my happening(?) hunger. (27)</l>
<l>Knowing, ah, the existence (28ab)</l>
<l>of kings on majestic elephants, (28)</l>
<l>	they won’t know of seeing [that]. (29cd)</l>
</lg>
